<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by Professor Andrew Le Sueur, Professor of Constitutional Justice, University of Essex (CRJ 01)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">by </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Professor </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Andrew Le </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Sueur</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">, Professor of Constitutional Justice, University of Essex (CRJ 0</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">9</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">I am Professor of Constitutional Justice in the School of Law at the University of Essex. This evidence is submitted in a personal capacity. My research </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">covers</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> constitutional aspects of courts and the judiciary, the idea of judicial accountability, and judicial review. </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Between 2006-09</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> I was the legal adviser to the House </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">of Lords Constitution Committee, which involved </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">practical process of scrutinising all government bills for their constitutional implications. I have participated in various unofficial working groups on constitutional reform, including one led by Stephen </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Hockman</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> QC and Professor Vernon </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Bogdanor</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> (see </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Hockman</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Bogdanor</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">, ‘Towards a codified constitution’ (2010) 7 </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Justice Journal </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">74) and the JUSTICE constitution committee report, </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">A British Bill of Rights: informing the debate</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> (JUSTICE, London, 2007).</span></li><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">I do not</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">believe that a codified constitution would be a </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">cure-all</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> for </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">the ills of the political system or </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">people’s</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> understanding of their rights and responsibilities as citizens (but it may help)</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> Reformers must be realistic about what will be achieved.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> My general position is that I favour codifying the principal rules relating to the British constitution in the form of an Act of the UK Parliament. I would like to see the preservation of the principle of parliamentary supremacy (so our elected representatives in Parliament would have the final say on the content of legislation) rather than constitutional supremacy (in which a judicial body would have veto on unconstitutional legislation). The main benefit of codification is </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">that it would help to differentiate the ‘rule</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">s</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> of the game’ from the ‘game’ and help politicians, officials and members of the public </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">distinguish</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> what is and is not a constitutional matter. Too frequently under the current system there </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">are </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">failure</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> to appreciate when a proposed government policy has </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">major</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> constitutional implications. The Act codifying rules of the British constitution should be entrenched</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> in some way (in other words, any attempt to repeal or amend its provisions should be subject to </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> procedural </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">constraint</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> beyond the need for the approval </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">by</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> a majority of MPs). </span></li><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">I welcome the Committee’s focus on the role of the judiciary in a </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">future </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">codified constitution (‘the UK Constitution’). This is clearly an important part of the overall design of the UK Constitution. Thinking about the topic generally, it is possible to envisage a range of possible roles. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">At the maximalist end of the spectrum would be a design that</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> (for example)</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> empowers the judges to adjudicate on the constitutionality of Acts of the UK Parliament with</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> a</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> remedial power to </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">quash</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> Acts that are incompatible with the </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">UK Constitution</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">; the UK Constitution might also include legally enforceable socio-economic rights (to health, housing, education and so on)</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">; there might also be ‘abstract’ judicial review of bills before they receive Royal Assent</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">. A design of </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">this sort would involve a shift </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">in</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> the balance of power to decide matters of national interest</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> away from the UK Parliament and Government towards the courts.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">A minimalist design of the judicial role in the UK Constitution would not give the courts power to quash Acts of Parliament (so preserving the existing principle</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> of parliamentary supremacy), </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">would avoid creating </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">justiciable</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> socio-economic rights (confining rights to the civil and political </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ones</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> familiar from the European Convention on Human Rights currently incorporated into national law by the Human Rights Act 1998)</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">, and would not have a system for abstract judicial review of bills</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Where on the maximalist-minimalist spectrum a UK Constitution should sit has to depend on (a) efficacy and (b) political acceptability. Efficacy is concerned with what is needed, from a ‘technical’ legal perspective, for the UK Constitution to make a real improvement compared to current constitutional arrangements. Political acceptability is about being realistic </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">as to</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> what political elites and the general public would find attractive or tolerable.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">In the current political climate it is </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">difficult to imagine that mainstream political opinion would </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">accept</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">an enlargement of the</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> role </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">of</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> judges </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">in adjudicating </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">on </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">legal questions that relate to controversial matters of public policy</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">. The </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">existing </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">powers of courts under the Human Rights Act 1998 and in judicial review claims are regularly called into question by members of the Government and have few champions within Parliament. </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">There is little public understanding of the role of courts in these areas and the constitutional function of the judges is routinely disparaged and misrepresented in the press. T</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">his political background against which the continuing debates about a UK Constitution take place is </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">un</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">likely to change in the foreseeable future. Politically </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">realistic</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> constitutional</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> reformers should therefore favour a minimalist role for judges in </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> codified constitution and provide reassurance to sceptics and opponents of judicial power that adoption of a UK Constitution need not involve the judges in </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">novel </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">legal tasks.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What is the constitutional role of the judiciary and in what principal respects would the role of change if the United Kingdom were to move towards a codified constitution?</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">current </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">role</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> of the courts</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> in the United Kingdom</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">in</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> adjudicat</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> on legal disputes rela</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ting to constitutional matters </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">include</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">:</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> (a) </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">determining </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">legal </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">disagreements</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> about the respective powers of different institutions within the constitution, for example between the UK Parliament and the UK Government, or between the central and local government</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">;</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> (b) </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">dealing with </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">legal questions about the </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">division of powers between the UK and the European Union, under the guidance of </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">preliminary rulings by </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">the European Court of Justice</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">;</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">c</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">adjudicating on </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">legal questions about</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">exercise of powers </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">by executive and legislative institutions in Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">in accordance with the </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">devolution settlements</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> created by the UK Parliament</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">; (d</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">) </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">protecting </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">fundamental rights of individuals, including those </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">in </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">the Human Rights Act 1998</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> taking into </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">account the case law of the European Court of Human Rights. </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The boundar</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">y</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> between the lawyers’ categories of </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">constitutional</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">administrative</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> law </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">is</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> flexible, but to the previous list could be added (e) judicial review of executive action and delegated legislation, ensuring that public bodies remain within the powers conferred on them by Acts of Parliament and operate in accordance with judge-made </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">legal </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">principles of (for example) fairness and rationality.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">A</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> codified UK Constitution could change aspects of </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">these functions</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> in </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">two </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">main </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">respects</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> – though</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> whether it does or</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> precisely how would of course depend on the final design of the new constitution</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">First, </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">c</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ourts would</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> probably need to</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">assume the role of adjudicating on </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">legal questions </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">relating to </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">whether Acts of Parliament are in conflict with the UK Constitution</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">In my view, </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">although such</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> a change </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">would be significant it </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">would not be a </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">revolution</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ary step</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">. J</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">udges under the current constitutional arrangements </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">already</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> adjudicate on the </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">compatibility</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> of legislation</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> is a variety of ways.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">W</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">here a claimant argues that a</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> provision in a </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">UK </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Act </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">of Parliament </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">conflicts with European Union law</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">; if found to be incompatible the</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> courts must ‘</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">disapply</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">’ the offending provisions</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">W</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">here a claimant argues that a provision in a UK Act of Parliament is incompatible with </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Convention rights</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">;</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> under the Human Rights Act 1998</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> if the courts cannot interpret the provision so that </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">it is compatible</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> (section 3)</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">, they may make</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> a ‘declaration of incompatibility’</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> (section 4)</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">he lawfulness of delegated legislation</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">, including that</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> debated and approved in Parliament</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> may be challenged in judicial review proceedings and quashed. Examples of this are </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Ahmed v HM Treasury (JUSTICE intervening</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">)(</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Nos</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> 1 and 2)</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> [2010] UKSC 5</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> (quashing </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">delegated </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">legislation intended to freeze assets of suspected terrorists</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> on the ground that </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">it </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">went beyond what was authorised by the United Nations Act 1946) and </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">R (</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Asif</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Javed</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">) v Secretary of State for the Home Department</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> [2001] EWCA </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Civ</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> 789 (delegated legislation making it easier to </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">return people</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> to Pakistan after refusal of asylum applications was held to be irrational). </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">he UK Supreme Court</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> may</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> adjudicate on whether bills and</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Acts of the Scottish Parliament, Measures of the National Assembly for Wales, and Acts of the Northern Ireland Assembly are in within the legislative competence of those institutions under the devolution Acts (see, for example, </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Attorney General v National Assembly for Wales Commission</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> [2012] UKSC 53)</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ul><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">A second change </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">(depending on the content and design of the UK Constitution) </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">might be that courts would be called on to adjudicate </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">on disputes about </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">rules</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> that are currently regarded as non-</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">justiciable</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> or outside the jurisdiction of the courts</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">. This would happen, for example, if </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">some </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">rules that are currently</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> non-legally </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">binding</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> c</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">onstitutional conventions</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> (many of which are now set out in the </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Cabinet Manual) </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">or rules relating to the internal working of the UK Parliament were incorporated into a new UK Constitution. The </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">character of these rules </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">are</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> not</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> appreciably different from rules in legislation – for instance, in terms of their precision and importance</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> and in and of themselves would not create any novel problems or tasks for the court.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> The inclusion of socio-economic rights in a UK Constitution would bring about a more significant change in the judges’ </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">influence on the direction of </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">some areas of </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">public policy</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What forms of consultation with the judiciary would be necessary to ensure that the legal and judicial implications of codifying the constitution were taken into account?</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">This will depend on the </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">overarching </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">process used to</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> design and</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> plan for the adoption of a codified constitution. </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The judiciary should be consulted about what form of consultation would be appropriate. UK governments have a poor track-record of consulting the judiciary on matters of constitutional importance affecting courts and judges, for example the 2003 announcement on abolition of the Lord Chancellor, creation of a UK Supreme Court and plans for a new system of judicial appointments and the creation of a Ministry of Justice</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> in 2006</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">. It would be important to the legitimacy of the constitutional design process for similar blunders to be avoided.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">It may be helpful to distinguish between </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">different </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">types of </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">implications</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">: (a) the opinions of judges individually and collectively on the </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">general</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> advantages and disadvantages of having a codified constitution; (b) the views of judges on the consequences of a codified constitution for </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">status and role of judges, in particular the constitutional principle</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> of judicial independence</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> and the rule of law</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">; and (</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">c</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">) the essentia</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">lly technical assessment </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">of the likely caseload and resource implications of a codified constitution</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">, which presumably would be carried out by the Ministry of Justice</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> HM Courts and Tribunals Service in conjunction with the judges.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Whichever institution is in charge of the design and implementation process for a new UK Constitution would need to bear in mind that the United Kingdom has three separate legal </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">jurisdictions,</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> each with its own head of the judiciary; additionally, the President and Justices of the Supreme Court would need to be consulted. In so far as the codified constitution may impinge on the Crown Dependencies (Jersey, Guernsey and the Isle of Man) and British Overseas Territories, the judiciary of those jurisdictions </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">may </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">also </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">need to</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> be consulted</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> (for example, on anything said about the Judicial Committee of the Privy Council, which is the final court of appeal for those jurisdictions)</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Also of note is the fact that </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">the judiciary no longer ha</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">serving </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">members in the House of Lords able to contribute directly to debates there (following the disqualification </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">from Parliament </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">of </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">serving</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> judges with peerages by the Constitutional Reform Act 2005). </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Whatever may have been the deficiencies of a </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">system in which judges had a place in the UK Parliament, one advantage was that what senior judges said in debate on the floor of the House was </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">clearly on the public record</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">. (There were several significant contributions by judges to the Constitutional Reform Bill debates</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> in 2004-5</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">).</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> Transparency should also </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">be a desirable characteristic</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> of any consultation </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">with judges </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">about the UK Constitution.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">If the UK were to have a codified constitution, what powers should the courts have if they held that a piece of legislation was unconstitutional? </span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">There are various possible designs for the court’s </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">remedial </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">powers in relation to an unconstitutional prov</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ision of a UK Act of Parliament, including the following.</span></li><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The court could have power to quash (or ‘strike down’) the unconstitutional provision. A consequence would probably be that any executive action already taken based on the provision would be unlawful.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> Careful consideration would need to be given as to whether the court should have power to suspend the </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">effect of a quashing order to permit </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">the Government and </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Parliament </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">time draft and deliberate on</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> legislation to rectify the incompatibility. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The court could have a power to ‘</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">disapply</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">’ the provision in the particular case being decided. This is the model used in relation to rules of national law held to be inconsistent with European Union law.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> In essence, this means that the court determines the case on the basis that the offending provision has no legal validity</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> (but stops short of </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">formally </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">quashing the provision)</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The court could have power to make a ‘declaration of incompatibility’ which ‘does not affect the validity, continuing operation or enforcement of the provision in respect of which it is given’ and ‘is not binding on the parties to the proceedings in which it is made’. This is the model used in section 4 of the Human Rights Act 1998 for situations where a provision of an Act of Parliament is held to be inconsistent with Convention rights.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ul><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">In my view, it would be preferable and politically realistic </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">to use the last of these models. This would</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">preserve</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> the principle of parliamentary </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">supremacy</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> insofar as the UK Parliament would retain the final say on whether and if so how to remedy the incompatibility</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The courts should have power to quash d</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">elegated legislation if it is incompatible with the UK Constitution</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">. This </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">currently happens when delegated legislation is held incompatible with Convention rights</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> under the Human Rights Act 1998</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> or unlawful </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">on other grounds</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> in judicial review proceedings</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">If there were a codified constitution, should the courts be able to assess the constitutional validity of a Bill before it becomes an Act? What would be the advantages and disadvantages of such a system?</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Constitutional </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">or supreme </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">courts in </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">many countries </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">have jurisdiction to carry out </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">abstract</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> review of proposed legislation before it is promulgated or comes into force. </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Indeed, within</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> the United Kingdom, the Scotland Act 1998</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">, the Northern Ireland Act 1998</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> and the Government of Wales Act 2006, empower the UK Law Officers to refer the question to the UK Supreme Court whether </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">proposed legislation being considered</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">by the</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> Scottish Parliament</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">, the Northern Ireland Assembly, or the National Assembly for Wales is within the legislature’s legislative competence</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The advantage</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> of including this type of arrangement in the UK Constitution </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">would be to</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">facilitate </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">a relatively speedy determination of uncertainty about the compatibility of legislation (though it would cause delay in the parliamentary legislative process) and </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">to </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">provide an authoritative view before executive action </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">s taken based on the legislation.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">If it thought that this type of review is desirable in principle, then several important features of the process would need to be designed. It would be necessary to decide who has the right to refer a question to the court (for example, only the Government, or shoul</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">d parliamentarians have the power?) Wh</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">o should frame the legal question f</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">or the court to adjudicate upon?</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">W</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ho should be permitted to make representations to the court</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> (it is easy to imag</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">in</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">e a large number of campaign groups wishing to intervene in the proceedings)? Who</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> would bear the cost of such proceedings (which one can envisage would be considerable)</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">? These points would require careful examination.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">There </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">would be</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">two</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> disadvantages</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> to including pre-Royal Assent review of bills in a UK Constitution</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">, which</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> lead</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> me to </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">conclude that the UK Constitution should not include such a procedure.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">First</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">, this type of review</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> would involve intermeddling legislative and judicial processes</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">, which wo</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">uld run</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> counter to </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">the</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> reforms</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> of the Constitutional Reform Act 2005</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">designed to introduce greater separation between parliamentary and judicial functions</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> in the UK constitution</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">al system</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> Judges </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">risk being</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> drawn into matters of politic</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">al contention at the height of a</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> controversy.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> If this type of review procedure could be limited to uncontroversial technical issues this could be avoided but it seems inherently unlikely that the procedure could be confined in this way.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> It may be thought better to leave pre-Royal Assent scrutiny to </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">parliamentary</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> institutions such as the House of Lords Constitution Committee and the Joint Committee on Human Rights</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> (or perhaps a new joint committee on constitutional scrutiny)</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">. Although the recommendations of these committees are not binding on Parliament or the Government, they operate to flag-up likely problem areas at bill stage</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> and help to inform political debate</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">A second disadvantage of pre-Royal Assent abstract scrutiny is that it would not prevent subsequent </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">concrete</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> review challenges being brought by individuals aggrieved by the </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">application</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">of </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">the legislation </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">by public bodies</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> A provision of an Act of Parliament that has been judged not to breach the </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">UK C</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">onstitution may </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">look very different once it is implemented in a particular way in specific circumstances.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> Any attempt to prevent such concrete challenges would be contrary to notions of the rule of law and quite possibly contrary to articles 6 and 13 of the European Convention on Human Rights (guaranteeing fair trials and effective remedies for breaches of Convention rights). </span></li><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">I concur with the assessment made by the House of Lords Constitution Committee that while a system of abstract review of legislation </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">might seem attractive in some respects, … it could compromise the impartiality of the senior judiciary and that it would not in any case prevent successful</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> concrete challenges (</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Relations between the executive, the judiciary and Parliament </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">6th Report of Session 2006-07, HL Paper 151, </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">para</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> 106).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Would a Constitutional Court function best as part of the Supreme Court, or should it be separate? If the latter, how should it be appointed?</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">In answering this question two main issues need to be addressed: (a) what expertise and life experience should a person adjudicating on constitutional law matters have? (b) </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">what</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> procedures are best for the effective handling of cases involving questions of constitutional law?</span></li><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">As to personnel, it is notable that a</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">lmost all countries that have a constitutional court separate from the mainstream court system also have a career judiciary in the mainstream courts, where relatively young and inexperienced lawyers are appointed as judges with a </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">civil service-like </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">career path mapped out in front of them.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> Some separate constitutional courts are able to appoint people who have a much wider range of experience, including backgrounds in the world of politics and academia.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> The common law tradition is different, preferring the mainstream courts to have judges appointed from among experienced mid-career lawyers. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">In line with my general view that judges in the senior courts of the United Kingdom are already adjudicating on constitutional law matters, it follows that I do not view the current judges as obviously inappropriate by reason of their professional expertise and life experience. As with other fields of law, it would be desirable to have multi-member courts able to draw on the expertise and experience of judges from a more diverse range of backgrounds</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> than is currently available</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> (and this is being addressed, though painfully slowly).</span></li><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The other issue is procedure: how would constitutional law disputes get to court? There seem to me to be advantages in using procedures similar to those already in place for dealing with public law matters. These differ in the three legal systems of the United Kingdom; my comments relate</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> only</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> to England and Wales. Part 54 of the Civil Procedure Rules </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">sets out a procedure</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> for claims for judicial review of executive action and delegated</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> legislation; this procedure may also be used for claims arising out of the Human Rights Act 1998. The procedure has two main steps: a claimant must first obtain the permission of the court (a filter mechanism based on written representations designed to dispose of obviously unmeritorious </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">claims expeditiously); if permission is granted, the claim may proceed to a full trial. </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The court of first instance is the Administrative Court (part of the Queen’s Bench Division within the High Court), with the possibility of appeals (with permission) to the Court of Appeal and the UK Supreme Court.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Requiring constitutional law </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">claims to start</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> in the High Court with the possibility of further courts would enable legal arguments to be refined if a case proceeds up the court hierarchy (something that would not occur if the UK Supreme Court is the court of first instance). In some cases it may be desirable to truncate the appeal process, with a case heard by the High Court leapfrogging the Court of Appeal to go directly to the UK Supreme Court.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">A further aspect of the design would relate to the possibility of ‘collateral challenge’ to</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> a provision of an Act of Parliament or executive action on grounds that it breaches the UK Constitution. So-called collateral challenge would occur when a person seeks to rely on the UK Constitution as a defence in a criminal or civil trial. Where such issues arise in lower courts or tribunals a system of case management and transfer should enable judges of appropriate seniority (</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ie</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> High Court judges) to decide the constitutional law issue.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 7.1pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">18 November 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>